data.title: Ginger Rogers Biography
data.meta_description: Read all about Ginger Rogers with TV Guide's exclusive biography including their list of awards, celeb facts and more at TV Guide.
data.text:
Fast Facts

Took the name Rogers from her stepfather, although she was never legally adopted by him

Was nicknamed "Ginger" by a cousin who could not pronounce "Virginia" correctly

Won the Texas State Charleston Championships at age 14

The prize was a spot on a traveling vaudeville show

First collaborated with Fred Astaire in 1933's Flying Down to Rio

The duo would eventually star in nine more Hollywood musicals together

Although best known as a dancer, she won her only Oscar in 1941 for her non-dancing role in Kitty Foyle

Published her autobiography, Ginger: My Story, in 1991

Awards

1953Golden Globe-Best Performance by an Actress in a Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy: nominated

1953Golden Globe-Actress in a Leading Role - Musical or Comedy: nominated

1942National Board of Review-Best Acting: winner

1941National Board of Review-Best Acting: winner

1940Oscar-Best Performance by an Actress in a Leading Role: winner

1940National Board of Review-Best Acting: winner
